article.headline: Drexel 56, Robert Morris 40
article.story: PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Gerald Colds scored 14 points, Tramayne Hawthorne had 11 and Drexel shot 50 percent from 3-point range in a 56-40 win over Robert Morris on Friday in the Philly Hoop Group Classic. The Dragons (4-1) play Loyola, Md. on Saturday in the Liberty championship game in the inaugural eight-team tournament at the famed Palestra. The tournament is broken up into two brackets, so there is no undisputed champion and a third-place game will also be played on Saturday. Hawthorne and Colds each sank three 3-pointers for the Dragons. Drexel went 7-for-14 on 3s to make up for a 9-for-23 effort from the free-throw line. Robert Morris (2-2) missed 15 of 16 3-point attempts. Mezie Nwigwe and A.J. Jackson led the Colonials with only seven points. The Colonials were impatient early, taking quick shots and failing to generate any consistent half-court offense. They missed all eight 3-point attempts in the first half and went 6-for-25 from the floor overall. Hawthorne and Colds hit consecutive 3s and Frank Elegar converted a three-point play to put the Dragons ahead 15-6. Colds and Hawthorne reversed the order but with the same result and sank consecutive 3-pointers during a 12-0 run that stretched the Dragons' lead to 17. Robert Morris coach Mike Rice, a former Saint Joseph's assistant, was whistled for a technical foul at the end of the first half. Hawks coach Phil Martelli, Rice's former boss, watched from his seat in the bleachers a few rows behind the Robert Morris bench. Martelli's son, Jimmy, is an assistant coach for the Colonials. Randy Oveneke made one of two free throws off the technical to open the second half and make it 33-14. Hawthorne followed with his third 3-pointer and the Dragons took a 22-point lead. The Colonials finally started playing well and cut a 22-point deficit to 12 with 11 1/2 minutes left in the game. Rice told his team in the huddle they had "plenty of time" to rally and catch the Dragons. Instead, Oveneke scored on a driving layup and barreled into teammate Evan Neisler with a congratulatory chest bump. Neisler added two free throws on the next possession as Drexel regained control of the game.
